project: CaseGen

description: >
  CaseGen is a single-page web app that helps designers generate structured case
  study drafts from project notes and screenshots using OpenAI. The draft format
  is always: Problem → Process → Decisions → Results.

stack:
  framework: Next.js (latest stable, App Router)
  language: TypeScript
  styling: Tailwind CSS (zinc/neutral palette)
  ai: OpenAI API (multimodal: text + images)

openai_model:
  preferred_model_string: "gpt-5.4-mini"
  requirements:
    - Must support vision (image inputs).
    - Must support JSON response format.
    - Never hardcode dated snapshots (e.g. gpt-4o-2024-08-06); use clean aliases.
  fallback_strategy: >
    If "gpt-5.4-mini" is unavailable, fall back to the latest available OpenAI
    model that supports both vision and JSON response formatting.
  verification_rule: >
    Before referencing an OpenAI model string in code, verify it is currently
    available in the API. Prefer the latest stable alias and avoid snapshots.

data_flow:
  - User fills `components/InputForm.tsx`.
  - `app/page.tsx` POSTs to `/api/generate`.
  - `app/api/generate/route.ts` validates input, calls OpenAI, returns JSON.
  - Response shape: { success, draft:{ problem, process, decisions, results } }.
  - `components/DraftOutput.tsx` renders the four draft sections and export actions.

constraints:
  - No authentication, no user accounts.
  - No database; nothing is persisted.
  - All AI processing happens server-side in the API route (never in client components).
  - Images are sent from the client as base64 strings in the API request body.
  - Must work as a PWA (installable on mobile).
  - Output structure is always exactly 4 string fields:
    - problem
    - process
    - decisions
    - results
  - OpenAI requests must use response_format: json_object.

pwa_checklist:
  goal: >
    CaseGen must be installable on mobile and behave like an app (PWA). Treat
    installability as a first-class requirement when making UI, routing, and
    asset decisions.
  required_assets_and_metadata:
    - Ensure `public/manifest.json` exists and is valid JSON.
    - Add a `<link rel="manifest" href="/manifest.json" />` in `app/layout.tsx`.
    - Set a consistent theme color (`<meta name="theme-color" ... />`) in `app/layout.tsx`.
    - Provide appropriate app icons (at least 192x192 and 512x512) in `public/` and reference them in `manifest.json`.
    - Ensure the app has a clear `name`, `short_name`, `start_url`, `display`, and colors in the manifest.
  offline_and_caching:
    - Decide and document an offline strategy (no offline, shell-only, or cached content).
    - If adding a service worker, keep it minimal and avoid caching API responses containing user data.
    - Never persist sensitive user inputs (notes, base64 images, drafts) in caches or storage.
  mobile_polish:
    - Verify tap targets are at least ~44px high and not cramped.
    - Ensure text areas, buttons, and copy/download actions are usable on small screens.
    - Avoid layout shifts; prefer stable heights and predictable spacing.
  verification_steps:
    - In Chrome DevTools, run Lighthouse and confirm PWA installability checks pass.
    - Confirm the install prompt appears (when eligible) and the installed app launches correctly.
    - Test on iOS Safari “Add to Home Screen” behavior (manifest + icons + theme color).

target_user:
  - Designers (product, UI/UX, brand, graphics)
  - Design-literate, quality-conscious, mobile-first

key_files:
  - app/page.tsx: Single page; owns state; renders InputForm and DraftOutput; triggers POST to /api/generate.
  - app/api/generate/route.ts: POST handler; receives notes + images; calls OpenAI; returns structured draft JSON.
  - components/InputForm.tsx: Textarea + image upload (max 5) + Generate button; collects user input.
  - components/DraftOutput.tsx: Renders draft sections; provides Copy to clipboard + Download .txt.
  - lib/prompt.ts: Exports SYSTEM_PROMPT and buildUserPrompt(notes, imageCount).

coding_style:
  - Add a one-line comment above every function explaining what it does.
  - Prefer explicit TypeScript types everywhere (props, params, return types); never use "any".
  - Keep components single-responsibility; move reusable logic into `lib/`.
  - Prefer simple, readable code over clever abstractions.

styling_rules:
  - Tailwind only; do not add external CSS files or CSS-in-JS.
  - Use a zinc/neutral palette by default; reserve accent colors for primary actions and status.
  - Aim for generous spacing and mobile-first layouts.

app_router_rules:
  - Use App Router conventions (`app/`); do not use `pages/`.
  - Use Server Components by default; add `"use client"` only when needed for interactivity/state.

dependency_policy:
  - Always use the latest stable versions of dependencies unless a specific version is required for compatibility.

assistant_working_agreement:
  - After each non-trivial edit, explain what changed and why in plain English.

